Tietz syndrome , also called Tietz albinism-deafness syndrome or albinism and deafness of Tietz , [1] is an autosomal dominant [2] congenital disorder characterized by deafness and leucism . [3] It is caused by a mutation in the microphthalmia-associated transcription factor (MITF) gene. [2] [4] Tietz syndrome was first described in 1923. [5] Contents Cause and Genetics See also References External links
Cause and Genetics Tietz syndrome has an autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance.
Tietz syndrome is caused by mutations in the MITF gene, located on human chromosome 3p14.1-p12.3 . [2] [4] [6] It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. [2] This indicates that the defective gene responsible for a disorder is located on an autosome (chromosome 3 is an autosome), and only one copy of the defective gene is sufficient to cause the disorder, when inherited from a parent who has the disorder.
